<div id="review_2989800970" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2989800970" />
    <a title="Susan&#39;s Reviews" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19736308-susan-s-reviews"><img alt="Susan&#39;s Reviews" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507651790p2/19736308.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2989800970?book_show_action=true">Sep 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan&#39;s Reviews" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan&#39;s Reviews" href="/user/show/19736308-susan-s-reviews">Susan&#39;s Reviews</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2989800970" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7763564893477431964">I have to thank Christine, a Goodreads friend, for telling me about Sonja Yoerg, who writes such beautifully interesting stories.<br/>Loving nature as I do, <u>True Places</u> was a balm to my soul! Thanks so much, Christine! Iris is found at the edge of a forest - feral, half starved and ill - by Suzanne, who was driving out in the country in an attempt to temporarily escape the pressures of her unsatisfactory life.<br/> In the end, it is Iris who rescues Suzanne, who has lost her identity and the courage to br</span>
  <span id="freeText7763564893477431964" style="display:none">I have to thank Christine, a Goodreads friend, for telling me about Sonja Yoerg, who writes such beautifully interesting stories.<br />Loving nature as I do, <u>True Places</u> was a balm to my soul! Thanks so much, Christine! Iris is found at the edge of a forest - feral, half starved and ill - by Suzanne, who was driving out in the country in an attempt to temporarily escape the pressures of her unsatisfactory life.<br /> In the end, it is Iris who rescues Suzanne, who has lost her identity and the courage to break out of the domestic trap she finds herself in. <br /><br />Iris's parents were minimalists, surviving out in the back woods of Virginia with little or no contact with the outside world. Iris is dismayed by all of the "things" that people find they can't live without, by massive consumption of goods and land, and by the wanton self-indulgence of the teens around her who seem so bored with life already. Suzanne's children, Brynn and Reid, and their respective issues in this novel are representative of our disenchanted youth of today. Pure and unspoiled Iris made me examine my own bad habits in this regard. <br /> <br />This book has something for everyone: Sonja Yoerg has a gift for describing nature - I could actually smell the damp pungent earth, hear a stream as it spilled over rocks, and identify the call of the birds she named from time to time. I love walking along the Humber River park lands and trails that stretch behind my apartment building, so these smells, sounds and sights are not a novelty for me. I am no camper, though, so reading about Iris lying down, alone, in the forest on a warm summer night actually gave me the creeps. (We have foxes and coyotes, even in the suburbs!)<br /><br />I really enjoyed this "family in crisis" novel. I agree with the author that we have to stop enslaving ourselves by our possessions, which steal our precious time because we have to work so hard to pay for them. I had a smile on my face at the end of this story: there is still hope for a better tomorrow. I rate this a 4.3 out of 5.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7763564893477431964" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


